No liberating amendment for Tymoshenko by parliament
The Ukrainian parliament today refused the request to abolish the paragraphs on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko had been convicted.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the release of the detained former prime minister, was rejected by MEPs at the second reading of the application for mitigation of the penalties for economic offences.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for concluding an allegedly detrimental contract with Russia to purchase natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final, in December the appeal of the convicted is to be negotiated in court.
Timoshenko himself describes the verdict as the regime’s political revenge, and even in the West the trial raised the suspicion of the court’s bias.
The motion to remove Section 365, on the basis of which the former prime minister was convicted, was supported by 147 deputies.
It would have required 226 votes.
