IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flight
Founded 100 years ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took over the name IBM only in 1924 - originally a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later IBM company was laid by the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the 80s of the 19th century.
They had technologies such as the famous puncture card watches to register the beginning and end of the work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the boss of the competition company Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
This leader then even overshadowed the founders of IBM – based on Watson’s ideas, the company’s invincible culture and identity continues to this day.
Watson managed the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began manufacturing and distributing all sorts of machines for trade - from sausage and cheese cutters, to cash registers.
Over the first four decades of Watson’s leadership, he doubled his revenues to nine million dollars, and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under its direction, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM technicians and computers helped guide NASA’s flights into space – to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969, man’s famous flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time came to market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultancy part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and entered the business of high-value consulting and services.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the last three years is the concept of “Smarter Planet”.
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas not even planned before, e.g. to improve the situation in traffic and city management.
In the trading sector, IBM recently launched the “Smarter Commerce” platform to help traders lead the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
Back in 1932, IBM established a branch in Czechoslovakia, the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM’R also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
Headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague, and there is also a world-class research team dedicated to voice recognition technology.
