Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five authorized state travel agencies in the former SSR: Edok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
At that time, the travel agencies only sold travel to the socialist countries of the Eastern Bloc, and only the chosen ones were allowed to travel to the West.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (German Democratic Republic - GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean Peninsula at the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern bloc (including Czechoslovakians) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the SSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel would not be possible.
Back then, the travel agencies also offered travel to the west, but then you had to accept huge snakes or also stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
This too was far from the end.
The so-called foreign exchange pledge - the condition for a trip to the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a foreign exchange pledge it would have been impossible to obtain the necessary funds (western currency) for a trip to the West.
Most Czechs spent their holidays in the country, so it’s no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates – a habit that continues to this day.
The velvet revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries all over the world.
A huge paradox that we are no longer aware of today is the fact that one could not travel to the most popular holiday country of the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation in the neighbouring Western European countries was lifted, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovakians simply couldn’t get enough of their trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to be there for at least a few days.
Thus, the Czech holidaymakers slept in a tent in the park when they traveled to Paris, because who would have had the money for accommodation in a hotel or pension at the time.
A typical feature of Czech foreign travel at the time was a trunk packed with canned, beer and permanent sausage etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the western currency freely.
Our level of life and, as a result, our average salaries increased, which resulted in another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, after 1997, travel agencies began to regularly prepare trips through charter flights, which made air travel incredibly cheaper compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the US, already had currency-free payments with all the advanced countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-saturate" travel came in 2000, when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was handled - to Thailand.
Since then, every year direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers fly to far away sunny countries; this year you fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
The 100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the era that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than CZK 15 per capita for a single holiday, including the cost of the resort.
