Europe's most beautiful pools
Jump into the blue
By Julia Stanek
Peddler pools in Ufo look, Prunkpools in Budapest: Those who travel through Europe can experience their blue wonder - and after a city tour or a hike rest their tired legs in sprudge pools.
A book shows where wellness in the water is best.
If Iris Meder went on a research trip in the past one and a half years, one thing was not to be missed in her baggage: her swimsuit.
Lying backwards on the water, she looked up in artfully designed domes, she swam towards marble pots waiting for her at the edge of the pool, and marveled at meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming halls.
If she liked a bath, she quickly added it to her notebook - with interesting details about the construction and history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools explored in this way - and now presents them in her recently published book "Badefreuden": Volksschwimmhallen in Munich, historic swimming palaces in the Black Forest, "Hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
Through 13 countries she led her "travel to the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe": in addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and one city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing culture enthusiast.
She doesn’t have much on her hat with sports, Meder says – only in the water it’s different.
Only annoying that swimmers have to settle with blue tiles and chlorine stench, while joggers can inhale the enchanting scent of spruce forests or listen to cheerful birdsong in the park.
“One day I wondered why swimming pools always have to be so ugly,” says Meder, who lives in Vienna.
"So I started collecting beautiful baths."
Water surface doubles architecture
Plucking in the plunge pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in bathrooms is so great, because all the senses are served, according to Meder.
And if the builders have made an effort, swimming pools can be a real eye-catcher: "In place of a floor, you have a water surface in baths."
"It is transparent on the one hand, but on the other it reflects the beauty of the entire building."
Everything visually doubles: high vaults, colorful tiles, springboards.
The small-format picture volume "Bathtime Joys" conveys information about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases on 190 pages - but above all makes you want to jump into the blue.
Notable specimens were discovered by the pool collector Meder during her research in Hungary.
In addition to splendid spas such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Bath in Budapest, she found a nitrate-containing water in a quaint karsh cave (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) and a thermal bath whose pools are filled with alkaline water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászén).
Spectacular views, on the other hand, offer many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria: While you have an eye on the whole city from the Zurich rooftop pool, you can look at the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton - and: In the steam room there is a window from which you can watch the hustle and bustle on the ski slopes.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: The Aquadome Ötztal looks like a Ufo just landed in the Alps.
It evaporates from three upwardly open shells in winter, while in the background the mountains of the Ötztal rise to the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool the pool collector Meder rose the smell of chlorine into the nose.
Many thermal baths smell like sulphur, and in the Arpád Bath in Békescsaba, Hungary, it smells so much like heating oil, which is hardly believed to have landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkali-hydrogen carbonate-containing healing water, which is almost black and whose sludge sticks to your skin as soon as you slide into the pool - a wellness experience of a special kind.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was also disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing spots: When she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing bath in the Czech city of Luhatschowitz, she found a closed terrain.
The bathroom, designed in 1902 by the architect Ducán Jurkovic, has now been closed.
As Meder glanced through the weathered windows of the red-and-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds growing between the tiles.
The decay, on the other hand, has been counteracted in a magical swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
Three phases of construction have already passed this bath; you can discover not only neo-Romantic elements dating back to its erection in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in Alhambra style, which was added around 1900.
Since its careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favorite pool of the pool expert Iris Meder - and not only because it originated from the Black Forest.
“It’s already an achievement to merge such different architectural styles into such a great unit,” Meder says.
With such a palace, diving in the thermal pool is apparently only a minor matter.
