21st house in Vienna
The Relocated Pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with ups, downs and a happy ending: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion of Brussels won prizes in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and got lost.
It is now reopened as an exhibition house.
When it comes to modern post-war architecture, clear shapes, glass halls, bold turns and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, the Austrian pavilion by architect Karl Schwanzer is a striking and famous example for the 1958 Brussler Weltausstellung.
Schwanzer’s pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d’Architecture for its light and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so famous that he also built Austria’s pavilion at the next world exhibition.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus a bowl-like auxiliary building in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, had been erected after the world exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the Vienna South Railway Station, rebuilt and opened a museum of the 20th century in 1962 - it was called the "20s House".
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna got a new house.
Since 2001, the building was empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21st house" and will be used as a museum for contemporary art in the future.
On Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a fortune in every way.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007, has achieved a new start.
Husslein-Arco, a PhD art historian with a considerable career, among others in her youth as an ice skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, emphatically implemented the conversion with politicians and conservationists, she procured public funds and private sponsorship funds and determined the use.
Apart from contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there was to be a café and a bookstore, and an office building had to be built for this purpose.
Strict supervision, small budget
Then Krischanitz was the ideal occupation for the implementation.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich’s Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but also because he studied with Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was an “enormously important place” for him, where he had watched the exhibitions “almost every weekend”.
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost its generosity and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and reused.
There were far greater problems with the current reconstruction: the building was "an energy sling," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facade were replaced, glass fiber-reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel beams have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been refurbished.
Two basements provided space for the new use, a lowered trench of light between the house and the street ensures exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light tail pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old reddish-brown anti-rust shade.
The movie theater is exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under strict supervision of the Monument Authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and also liked the Heritage Office," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rugged floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and conversions, the building has remained flexible and lightweight.
It was difficult with the pavilion, "which came from Brussels," Krischanitz recently said, a typical "drop-in-the-city story."
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "raise a real consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21st house is not in the wrong place, because there has been a city-building fortune: around the Swiss Garden is just the completely new planned "Hauptbahnhofsquartier", with office and residential houses.
And another lucky event may happen: The 21er house could be reinforced by another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin Temporary Kunsthalle, and it is heard that she is already negotiating with the city for a neighborhood location in the Swiss garden.
