Smart Crows Spread in Cities
In many places, seed crows are considered "problem birds": but the highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven out of the cities, experts claim.
Some like them, others want to get rid of them very quickly: crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many municipalities resident complaints about dirt and noise of the animals accumulate.
A remedy against the “problem birds” is not yet in sight.
Seed crows are no longer to get out of the cities, experts said at the first crow symposium in East Frisian Leer.
There, experts from all over the federal territory discussed possible ways out.
You are looking for alternatives in cities
Naturalists attributed the problems in cities to the rural escape of the particularly protected seed crows: the use of chemicals in agriculture increasingly destroys the traditional habitats.
Hunting, increasing cultivation and the felling of typical breeding trees made life difficult for the birds.
Crows are protected by nature.
Large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs exist in the Westphalian Soest, in the northwest among others in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen as well as in Leer.
There, in 2005, a controversial project for the mass killing of crows in the county had provided negative headlines.
Critics had called the catching of animals in bird traps and slapping them with clubs particularly brutal.
"The normal displacement, the greasing, is of no benefit," said the city and landscape planner Werner Klöver from Leer.
Spraying nests with water or cutting down trees often has undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
“The animals are leaving, large colonies are splitting up and spreading out in other places.”
Ceramization is only conceivable as an exception to hospitals, retirement homes or schools.
“We have to live with them, we can’t get them away.”
Without the surroundings, the problem cannot be solved in the cities, said Mayor Wolfgang Kellner from Leer.
It is conceivable to combine grazing of the animals from sensitive living areas and lock offerings to resettle them in other places.
On the other hand, the psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens advertised a completely different approach to the animals: "A pimple on the face is the best way to endure it confidently."
Jürgens had co-founded the Ascheberger Krähen-Lehrpfad in Schleswig-Holstein, where signposts inform about the life of the highly intelligent seed crows.
The project has already been accepted by tourists.
Jürgens also had his own opinion on criticism of the noise of the birds: "There is a lot of communication, they have a lot to say."
The intelligence and skill of the animals are legendary: Seed crows not only use tools to get a treat, but even make their own tools.
Behavioural researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested on four seed crows how far the intelligence of the birds reaches.
In one experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to collapse a scaffold with stones in order to get to a moth larva.
Without much training, they purposefully realized what size and shape a stone must have to make the platform collapse.
In a second attempt, the clever crows then had to solve a more tricky problem.
In a vertical cylinder, the researchers had placed a small bucket with a moth larva.
With the beak, the birds could not reach their prey.
However, the researchers had laid pieces of wire on them.
From this, all four animals formed a hook, with the help of which they then fished the bucket at the handle out of the tube.
Three of the four seed crows even managed to do so right away.
