Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Watch You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many guys who broadcast their anti-immigration opinion online.
On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to having committed his first public hearing in a July shooting in Norway, killing 77 people.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time before his attack in front of his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social networks.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
It’s easy – you just have to log in to Facebook.
“We found it wasn’t hard to come to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the British idea factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook’s hiding of personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply need to use the page’s advertising tool to accurately define their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy – just as marketers have for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with Adds, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the Adds invited users to a survey asking about their education, attitudes toward violence and their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 followers of 14 extremely right-wing parties in 11 European countries – without even having to leave their office once.
"It's a fairly new research method," Bartlett says.
Some of the results are hardly surprising. Online promoters of far-right groups are mostly young, male, and annoyed with immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, “those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more rational, democratic, and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screens.”
DEMO’s work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends such as in “likes”, text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three content per day, Facebook’s “data supernova” is generating a research boom that has increased the number of scientific papers named this page in the title by nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that you can study people through this page that you usually don’t reach on the street with your clipboard.
“If you used to try to question people of the British National Party, it was very hard to identify them.”
“They had to inform the party first and it would never have allowed them to enter,” Bartlett says.
“With Facebook, it all falls away – you go straight to them.”
Others say the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno from the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their full-blown frenzy on Facebook were significantly more prone to problem drinking than students who were silent about this topic.
Moreno suggests that peer-to-peer students, such as residential advisors, monitor the site and help a student when posting too many status updates.
“You can’t solve a problem unless you’ve realized it,” said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno’s co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle, the Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify vulnerable children who would not otherwise have been found."
Facebook also constantly collects the data of its own people.
The site’s data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, voter turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Happiness Index (primarily using data that only Facebook has access to – Master of Digital Freedom has long known that the site should make its big data fund available to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they want to or not. To be able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you allow the site to provide its own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how to collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
“I don’t think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, to a 2006 study in which he examined the public pages of students on Facebook.
“As far as she is concerned, it was only about her and her friends.”
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research participant is absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much of the information in a user profile and in posts is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn said.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks that a clipboard and pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
