7 Lessons of Interview with Deceased Steve Jobs Shown at a Theatre This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, highlighting the engineering genius as a great modern inventor.
What Apple fans find perhaps the most revealing in the recently rediscovered job interview, which was dusted this week before special film screenings in key markets, is how much this creative head has understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer, and self-appointed hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer who was eager to craft charts -- a man who believed many executives were suffering from "a disease of thinking," "that a really great idea makes up 90 percent of the work... [but] there is an enormous amount of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the television series "Triumph der Fachidioten" about the break-up of the personal computer, and he sat together for more than an hour with jobs in which they had one of the rare, detailed conversations.
By that time, more than 10 years had passed since jobs had been pushed out of Apple, and he was already working hard on his new computer company, NeXT, looking forward to the widespread adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringley’s interview was used in specialist idiots, he says the interview’s copy templates were missing on delivery.
It wasn’t until after Jobs’ death that a complete VHS copy was discovered in the director’s garage.
This slightly reworked footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview", which will be released on the Landmark Theatre this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate detailed interviews, Jobs seems surprisingly eager to explain his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In the course of the interview, there are four longer pauses between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds of meditation, in which Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts and strives for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to light when he seems impatiently responds to Cringely’s questions and pushes him to respond more quickly to topics or side-actions of greater importance.
Recorded before the era of Pixar, iPod, or iPhone, the Lost Interview somehow seems eerie far-sighted when Jobs evaluates what other companies think are right or wrong and presents its own vision of the future of the computer.
It’s one thing to read posthumous appreciations of Jobs’ career, but seeing jobs here as the eager dreamer on the way to greatness is something completely different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of how things could and should be.
Shortly after he had done all of this, he left and did it.
A quick look at seven remarkable sequences of the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a business:
"During all the years in business, I always ask, "Why are you doing things?". And the answer you always get is, "Oh, that's how it's made easy."
No one knows why he does what he does. No one in the business really thinks deeply about things.
That's what I found.
Jobs continues his efforts to streamline accounting at Apple.
Stunned by how costs were recorded - usually started with "standard costs", which were quantified on the mere assumption and then adjusted with "deviation" - he developed an automated factory that ensured that business costs could be determined down to the smallest.
How the pope became obsolete:
Jobs talks about the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device that could be used to sneak into the telephone company and conduct long-distance calls for free.
Much has been written about the device, but Job’s enthusiasm when he describes the Blue Box as an act of self-empowerment is contagious.
He describes how Wozniak and he would test the box by using a paid phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while looping through as many satellites as possible.
“We sent things half a dozen times around the globe and when you screamed into the phone, it came out a minute later in the phone next door,” Jobs says.
“We were young and we learned that we can build something ourselves that can control trillions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
We both didn’t know much, but we were able to build this little thing that can control a gigantic thing, that was an incredible lesson and I don’t think there would be any Apple without it.
Jobs goes on to tell of a glorious prank that Wozniak and he almost pulled off when they called the Vatican in the middle of the night via Blue Box and wanted to talk to the pope while they were able to do the best they could to imitate Henry Kissinger.
Since several members of the Catholic hierarchy were called in the middle of the night to talk to the American diplomat, the two had to laugh before the pope himself came on the phone.
How he fell in love with technology (and called Bill Hewlett unprepared):
At the age of 12, when he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he searched for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after her 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a part-time job at Hewlett-Packard for the summer.
"That had a remarkable impact on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my views on what a company was and how well it treated its employees."
Later, Jobs became one of the HP employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
He was the size of a suitcase, had a small screen with brownish tube and I fell in love with him.
I would climb up at HP as a teenager and hang on to this machine and write programs for it.
How to improve innovation:
Several times in the interview, Jobs talks about how to spontaneously invent new products.
Early in his career, when he was installing some boards, he was asked by a client to assemble the whole computer.
He worked with a payment deadline of only 30 days and had to think through both the assembly and the delivery of the finished equipment.
Later at Apple, he remembers the problems he had in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember piercing arguments... they yelled at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15, which was incredibly credible.
About large companies that are slowing down:
Long before he revived Apple, Jobs foresaw the paths that so many industrial giants stumbled upon with their visions and lost control of their stocks.
“Say you’re working at IBM or Xerox, so you’re doing a better copier or printer, so what?”
You own the stock monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [those people] are ultimately running the companies and the product that pushes people out of decision making.
The product genius that has led to this monopoly position is eliminated by people who have no concept of good products vs. bad products - craftsmanship necessary.
This happened with Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
You could have been ten times bigger if it had been Microsoft in the 1990s.
You got the defeat of victory.
About innovation as an art form:
"There's a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... if you develop this great idea, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about his subtleties.
You have to make votes, certain things that you can't, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5000 things, these concepts, and bring them all together...
Ultimately, it comes down to the taste, it comes down to trying to deal with the best stuff that humans have created and then trying to bring those things together to make what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We are always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who work there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happen to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it hadn’t been the computer industry, they’d be doing fantastic things in other areas.
