How to Debunk a Lie
A look at the current headlines shows how worrying and widespread deception and lies are in daily life.
The Republican presidential candidate, Herman Cain, is busy mastering the allegations of sexual harassment by several women, both of whom are accusing each other of lying.
Penn State’s leadership is accused of perjury for allegedly withholding reports that a retired football coach sexually abused a boy.
Last week, an open microphone was heard when French President Nikolas Sarkozy told US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitor Anthony Weidner was fooled when he circulated denials that were very quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of campaign funding violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that triggered President Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term in the Oval Office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Stories about cheating in school and at college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents where teachers have given their students the exam answers so that they could stand well even in their performance checks.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lying and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
Many of these lies are considered to be lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognizing or "discovering lies" is one that is important for every person to learn, and this for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from a societal game like Sharades, in which the goal is to call out “Have yourself!”, uncovering a deception is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that conducted far-reaching research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most ancient myths about lying have been uncovered.
Lies look you in the eye.
They don’t always stutter, stem, blush, and fidge.
However, it should not be inferred that these liars are difficult to uncover and uncover.
An experienced lie-debunker can penetrate to the truth by learning something about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, about questioning and timing.
I have spent several years investigating the scientific results of the extensive and ever-growing field of debunking, and it is clear that uncovering a deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us to find our way in our complex world, especially if hiring or questioning people or negotiating or administration is one of our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at appraising other people, arousing their interest and controlling their own emotions, and they intuitively feel how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to the research, we know that extroverts lie more often than introverts that men are more likely to appear to be “self-oriented” lies than women whose lies are more “oriented” – usually to protect the feelings of others – that married people are less likely to lie to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are mostly “fat” lies).
We also know that when one person has been exposed as an offender, others feel less guilty about lying to that person.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, by observing that person’s normal behavior.
This is called baselining, the starting position.
It specifies a reference point for later evaluating changes.
Observe the attitude, laughter, voice quality of their subject.
You should know better when someone is usually constantly tripling their feet so they don’t wrongly accuse them if they triple their feet during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of conspicuous verbal and non-verbal behaviors.
Think of these accumulations as alarm bells that shrill, not as evidence of unmasking.
People who are fooling may be frozen when they try to remember their story. Maybe their feet point towards the door or they lean towards the exit, change their position in a significant way, or show a "relaxation after the hiring conversation," this deep, relaxing exhalation and the change in attitude when all the hard questions are over.
Askers often erroneously signal that a recruitment interview is over just to keep an eye out for that relaxation after the recruitment interview.
Also, pay attention to your subject’s language.
Scott Peterson’s slip-out is famous when he used the past form when he claimed his dead wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Deceiving people can also use a distancing language: "I didn't have a sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if you repeat a tricky question in general.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when answering a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth... as far as I know... to the best of my knowledge and conscience."
This makes the answer more perceptive than factual, often causing the alarm bells to ring.
There is no magic to unmask lies, but you can learn skills that make unmask possible.
Thanks to these skills, anyone can become less likely to fall victim to scammers, both in private and professional life.
