A New York family claims that the disco diva Patti LaBelle in the lobby of her Manhattan building had a tob addiction attack that would have scared her little daughter so much that she surrendered in fear.
The tirade of the “Lady Marmalade” singer scared 18-month-old Genevieve Monk so much that she suffered from “personality changes, sleep disorder” and “an increased fear of strangers,” her family told the Supreme Court in Manhattan.
It was on November 10 last year that stage worker Kevin Monk, his wife Roseanna, a kindergartener, and Genevieve wanted to set off for a family trip.
While Kevin Monk was picking up the car, Roseanna Monk went with the luggage and Genevieve on her arm to the lobby in her building on Riverside Boulevard.
Roseanna Monk said she stopped near the door and dropped her daughter off for a moment.
"Someone showed up behind me and said, 'Do you know what your daughter is doing right now?' I said, 'Yes,' and went to take her back on her arm," she said.
LaBelle exhorted the pregnant woman.
“She said in an aggressive tone, ‘You shouldn’t drop your daughter off near the door,’” Roseanna Monk said.
I told her, "I don't care what you say or think."
She got angry and began to scold - she used the F-word and the A-word and became very loud.
She had a bottle of water in her hand and started tipping water from the bottle on me.
She said Genevieve had become hysterical.
“I said to this woman, ‘Look what you did to my daughter,’” said the child’s mother.
LaBelle plunged onto the mother, who was still wearing Genevieve on her arm, and had to be restrained from her companion and pulled to a waiting car, Roseanna Monk said.
The baby screamed so much that it had to surrender, she said.
Later, the LaBelle family asked for an apology in writing, but received no response.
LaBelle’s lawyer and representative did not respond to calls asking for a statement.
The lawsuit is on an unspecified compensation, but family lawyer Sam Davis said he will not charge a fee and plan the family to donate the money they receive to child cancer aid.
“We want Patti LaBelle to take responsibility for her behavior,” Davis said.
"This kind of behavior is absolutely unacceptable, especially if it is shown to a kindergartener wearing an 18-month-old baby on her arm."
Climate constraints slowed the economy
In the first year that Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and black work rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in Sinaloa’s economic history. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who describes himself as the initiator of change and fueled great hopes for economic growth, is in government. However, due to the climatic adversities, growth cannot be spoken of, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused million-dollar losses in agriculture, but also limited the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first quarter, mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development by 31.16 percent, which had a decelerating effect on other economic sectors.
According to a report published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development), 582 000 hectares of agricultural land have been damaged, 78.03 percent of which have been completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent have been partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity until November has steadily increased unemployment in the Mexican state. In the first quarter of the year, the Instituto Nacional de Estadistica y Geografia observed a rapid increase in unemployment, since from January to March 55 053 inhabitants of Sinaloa had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 percent in the following quarter, and from July to September.
Lower liquidity
The economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments, the policy of public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently seeing is an increase in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including liquidity losses in the market as a result of the cuts in funds passed by legislation to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who are illegally accumulating dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them, or use them for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that the growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has decreased. This is due on the one hand to the problems of entry and on the other hand because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here and look for work here, which increases unemployment," he says.
Blackwork
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if you take into account the high proportion of black work, which, according to INEGI, includes 60.38 percent of workers in the country who work without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and undeclared labour are the lowest wages in all of Mexico, according to statistics from the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institute) and the Secretaria del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Office for Labour and Social Welfare in Mexico).
By September, the average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos, much less than the general government average of 7375 pesos.
Decrease in ADI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and growing unemployment, the strongest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the last ten years was recorded in 2011, according to the Secretarial Office of Economia (State Economic Authority), the ADI was $ 630 597 from January to June, representing a drop of 87.74 percent compared to the $ 5,143 312 in the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the Secretaria de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Governmental Authority for Economic Development) recorded a total investment of 17,280,000 pesos in 2011, mainly from tertiary companies.
The debt
In the light of the economic crisis, the state government applied to the National Congress in July for a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities in order to reactivate the economy.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, the first year of government made Mario López Valdé's incapacity manifest.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Manufacturing in Mexico), stated that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the state government.
"Economic activity in Sinaloa has been really poor this year, and we need to work hard to regain the land lost this year, and we need to double our efforts in 2012. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the already well-coordinated government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made the country’s economic development more difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important impacts is a slowdown in the economy, which is not sufficiently moving to create an economic dynamic that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services, so we will close the year well below our expectations," he said.
redefine the vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la Repáblica Mexicana in Sinaloa, said that the state should be encouraged to engage in more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the country's economic vocation and line, because it is important to activate all Sinaloa's material and human resources," he said.
There is much to do
The chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that will guide the government’s efforts in better direction.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he explained.
He stressed that the current state power has made progress in government.
"There are areas where you can say that the government has acted more comprehensively, and what I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
Arrested for 8 kg of marijuana
A resident of Navolato was sentenced to five years in prison and 100 days sentences for owning eight kilos of marijuana.
The Republic’s public prosecutor’s office announced that the drug retailer was Omar Alexis Valenzuela Sandoval, who was punished for a public health offense – here the commercial possession of marijuana.
According to the AP/SIN/CLN/687/2010/M-I file, Valenzuela Sandoval was arrested on 7 June 2010 by Mexican military personnel during the surveillance of the Cipriano Valdez road opposite the guard post No. 80 in the village of El Castillo, Navolato.
The drug retailer drove in a white van storing a black bag in a box in the car and in the passenger seat a small backpack in which the military found eight kilos and 23 grams of marijuana.
For this reason, the confiscated goods were handed over to the district judge and the punished person is still in the prison.
Debt for construction work
The social buildings for migrants provided for in the Hábitat, Rescate de Espacios Páblicos and 3x1 programs run the risk of not being completed due to lack of funds or only with a great delay, said Miguel Angel López Miranda.
The head of the Urban Social Development Authority stated that although the construction programs are already advanced, they are now in danger, as the state government has not paid the funds it owes, which exceed 11 million peso for the three programs.
He said the total investment in these three programs amounted to almost 50 million pesos, of which 25 percent fell to the state, and so far only the Federación and the municipality have contributed funds to the construction work, so a delay in the construction termination is expected.
"Twelve million they have to contribute, and although the year is already coming to an end, they have not given us a penny, and that even though they should have paid us a portion in July," he said. "To be not too late, we have already begun the construction work, and they are already far advanced, but we need the money."
He pointed out that under the government of Jesus Aguilar Padilla, the state had failed to meet its obligations, so the municipality had to take out a loan of 7 million at the beginning of its reign, equivalent to the amount that the central government would have had to raise.
"We had already done this in the last legislature, because the state did not have sufficient economic resources. The programs continued and this year we had to get the funds that the state had not raised to participate in these programs," he said.
Even though the state authorities were obliged to pay out these funds, he commented that the Minister of Administration and Finance had been requested to speed up the administrative work and pay out the outstanding share as soon as possible.
“They have to contribute almost 12 million, and although the year is already coming to an end, they have not given us a penny.”
The court approves the transition to digital television in Mexico for 2015
The changeover from analogue to digital signals has been one of the most important changes in the world in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional lawsuits filed by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the presidential decree, under which the switch from analogue to digital signals from 2021 to 2015 must be moved, due to the lack of eight votes required to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, felt that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his responsibilities when he issued the legislative decree detailing the switch to terrestrial digital television.
This decision rejected the constitutional dispute created by the Senate, because it did not receive the required qualified majority of eight votes for the court to decide on constitutionality or non-constitutionality.
In the project for the lawsuit, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, it was proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional, since the regulations relating to radio and television would be subject to the Commission Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico), which is why the decree would contradict the hierarchical principles and laws.
In favor of the project, only Zaldivar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the Legislative Decree. After accepting the lawsuits, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the Legislative Decree and ceased all activities to set up the digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the lawsuit filed by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the debate on the project, for which Minister Sánchez Cordero was also responsible.
In his contribution, the Prime Minister expressed his disagreement with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the country government may not regulate with general rules the measures that the public administration should take.
"I also don't think that doing so would affect the independence of the regulatory body," she recalled, "that the central government is responsible for planning strategic policies, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, because it is the central government that is in charge of state affairs.
Replacing analog signals with digital is one of the most important changes that has taken place around the world in recent years, and it brings about better use of the radioelectric spectrum, increased quality of the signal and more channels.
The postponement of the changeover, she said, is a postponement of the exploitation of digitization, which is a decision in the public interest, which has not only technical aspects, "because it includes economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "required the action of the entire system, according to the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a group of features that the constitution puts in the hands of the central government."
It recalled that many countries around the world had already implemented the digital transformation, namely the government, despite having highly specialized facilities.
It cannot be concluded that the government would intervene in the competences of Congress with the publication of the contested legislative decree, because the laws passed by the legislature would be complied with,” she assured.
The possibility of counting the ballots in Michoacán individually is considered
According to PREP, the difference between first and second place in the election of the governor is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
The possibility of individual counting of the ballots is a reality in the Michoacán elections this year, because according to the data issued by the Programa de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the governoral elections is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
With this in mind, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just last November 9th, the electoral office had adopted a series of regulations to harmonise local regulations with state reforms in electoral matters.
It should be remembered that Michoacán had not adapted his political constitution, his electoral law or his law on electoral justice to the reforms passed by Congress, so that they did not enter into force at this round of elections.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional lawsuit filed by the local legislature and judged the state commissioner’s vote on the constitutional reforms as “invalid and unlawful” as he did not have the right to “decline or veto it.”
In an interview on the possibility of individual counting of the votes, Maria de los Angeles Llanderal said that thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, there was now a possibility that the local electoral authority could partially or completely count the ballots.
Thus, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be partially counted The results in the minutes are not in agreement; the minutes on the counting and calculation of votes are not in fact available or are not in possession of the chairman of the electoral committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
In addition, the total counting of the fully completed ballots can take place if there is a difference between the suspected winner and the one standing in second place, which is equal to or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of the named candidates.
The counting of votes may also take place in its entirety if, after completion of the ordinary calculation, it is established that the difference between the suspected winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one percent, provided that an explicit request is made by a representative of the party whose candidate has become second, in which case the election packages that have been subjected to a partial counting would be excluded.
It is worth noting that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between the first and second places is just under 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
His Last Will
His ashes will be scattered across the Zapalinamé Mountains, the family confirms.
The remains of the pilot Felipe Bacio Cortés settled on Saltillo, his birthplace, this Sunday evening.
According to family members, the lieutenant's last will was that his ashes be scattered across the Zapalinamé Mountains.
After a ceremony, the family of Bacio Cortés returned to the capital of Coahuila, along with the others who died in the crash, in an airplane of the Mexican Air Force.
At noon the ashes of the lieutenant-colonel landed on the mourning hall, which is located on the Boulevard Nazario Ortiz Garza, and where the family members and friends came.
At 5.30 p.m., his remains were examined at the Institute of Technology of Saltillo, which was initiated by his former classmates from the technical high school and his American football team, to whom Felipe Bacio belonged during his preparation for the high school.
"He wanted to return to Saltillo and to have his ashes spread over the Zapalinamé Mountains, which he had always told his family and friends," Sandra Bacio Cortés, the pilot's sister, said in a statement.
From her point of view, the Lieutenant-Colonel had fulfilled all his dreams and she believes that he had stood in the fullness of his life. "He was a successful man, exceptional as a father and as a son, a loving brother and he always stood up for his family."
Felipe Bacio Cortés left Saltillo very young to enter the school of the Air Force of Zapopán, Jalisco.
Some couldn’t believe it because they thought it would even make him dizzy on a truck, yet he was always striving to realize his dream of becoming a pilot.
His nephew Jorge Alberto Dávila Bacio remembers him as a good man. "He had barely arrived in Saltillo, and the whole family wanted to welcome him, as on the occasion when he brought Martha Sahagan to Saltillo."
The young man recalls that even at the age of seven, he had traveled to Zapopán to graduate his family member, so he knows that his uncle died when he did what he liked best: flying a plane.
One last goodbye
Lieutenant Colonel Felipe Bacio Cortés of the Mexican Air Force was honored by the people and government, the Mexican army of the Sixth Military Territory, the Mexican Air Force, headmasters and students of the Saltillo Technological Education Institute, where he studied in 1985 and was outstanding in both studies and sports.
Bacio Cortés died a few days ago when the helicopter he flew, which also included Secretary of State José Francisco Blake Mora and six other people from the same authority, crashed.
At 6.05 p.m., the cremated remains of Bacio Cortés, citizens of Saltillo, arrived to be handed over to members of the Mexican Air Force, led by Major Jaime Martinez, in the courtyard of the barracks, where he was already awaited by his family members, including his daughter Amanda and his wife Cristina, his mother, siblings and other relatives.
