Formation of the new Italian government on Wednesday
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, meets with the President of Italy tomorrow to introduce him to the new government that is to face the crisis that has led Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, meets with the President of Italy tomorrow to introduce him to the new government that is to face the crisis that has led Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
A statement from the Presidential Palace announced that Monti, who was appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm the formation of the government.
It is assumed that he will present a cabinet composed of a majority of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new prime minister will take office.
Monti said he would present to the president the results of the talks with the political parties on government formation.
“I would like to reaffirm my absolute confidence in our country’s ability to cope with these difficult times,” the former EU Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the formation of government, but his comments show that the obstacles have been overcome.
The “frame is now well laid out,” he added.
Monti has managed to form a government in less than three days, which is much less time than normal, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed the costs of debt to an unbearable level.
The new government, led by former EU Commissioner Monti, must adopt a tough austerity package demanded by Europolitics to regain the weakened confidence in Italy.
The pressure on Monti to be in a hurry was intensified by the fluctuating market situation as a result of which Italian government bonds were charged with 7 percent interest for 10 years, in line with the situation in which Greece and Ireland were forced to apply for the European bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian industrial association Confindustria, told the press after a meeting with Monti: "We said we would do our best to support this government."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti’s chances of success were significantly increased with the support of the PDL party of Silvio Berlusconi, who had to resign on Saturday as a result of the crisis.
“We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti are intended to bring about good results,” said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party.
The support of the PDL, the largest party in Italy, is essential, because so far many of its members have opposed a government made up of a majority of technocrats, which is currently forming Monti.
Support from Parliament
The new Monti government needs strong parliamentary support to implement the probably unpopular austerity measures.
Resistance to its efforts or delaying reforms could once again cause a devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks also puts pressure on Monti’s failure to act as a disaster.
Monti began his debates on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business associations, as well as with youth and women’s organisations.
The session will be closed on Tuesday evening.
Monti was appointed this Sunday by Napolitano, who initiated an extremely rapid change of government in response to the crisis.
After a short breathing at the end of last week, when it became known that Berlusconi would resign, as a result of uncertainty about the success of the new Prime Minister, the costs of Italian government bonds have again reached critical limits.
Saving Italy with a national debt of 1.8 trillion euros would be too much for the current EU bailout.
Monti said his government should last until the next elections, which are expected to be held in 2013, despite the predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms, rather than prefer the elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that this should only be made up of technicians, an indication of their concerns in the face of the process imposed by the pressure of the financial markets.
Political sources point out that the mutual mistrust and disagreements between the parties complicate the involvement of people from political life.
