The quintet included Costa Rica in its tour to celebrate its 20th anniversary
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament says the band is prepared to give one of their best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They were expected for more than 20 years, but the band reassures that a dream come true for them when they play in Costa Rica.
This was assured by bassist and co-founder of the group, Jeff Ament, who gave Viva an exclusive interview from Brazil last week.
The band is in the South American part of their tour to celebrate their 20th anniversary and on Sunday, the 20th, they make their only stop in Central America.
On this day, they perform at the National Stadium from 7:30 p.m. with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You can read an excerpt from the conversation, the full copy of which can be found in the online edition of La Nación.
For your Costa Rican fans, a dream comes true when Pearl Jam plays in Costa Rica: Are you aware of what this means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true for us.
This is just the second time we’ve played in South and Central America, and so far it’s been great.
I have only been to Costa Rica once for a holiday. It is such a beautiful country that we will definitely stay there for a few more days.
It’s exciting for us to bring our music there.
I ask you this because the fans of the band are completely devoted. They experience the days before the concert most intensely.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for being by our side all these years.
We took almost 21 years to come to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry to have taken this long to come here.
Some people even think that your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Doesn’t that put a little pressure on your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we’ve done in the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We played a couple of gigantic shows in Sao Paulo and we hope they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
Really, we want to play there.
We love this country, we love surfing and are thrilled by the jungle. For this, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always gone surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua. Together with Mexico, these are excellent areas for surfing. In this way, we learned about people who love surfing.
With a view to the tour you have offered huge shows with many songs.
What are your plans for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we’ve never played there, we don’t set any limits.
We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why?
I think that’s partly because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs, and everyone likes a different song, so the decision we’re going to make isn’t easy.
If we include two or three songs that we have not played in a long time, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs, otherwise they could be forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us, and I think that’s why it’s also interesting for the audience.
With this tour you celebrate your twenty-year history.
When you look back, is it hard for you to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I don’t think any of us ever imagined playing in a great rock band for more than 20 years.
We also continue to rely on this blessing and it is great to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and are excited to produce music.
We are lucky to be able to go to the places in the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't stand better.
What did it mean for you to participate actively in the birth of the Grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of great bands.
We are good friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It’s surprising and abundantly unusual when a movement comes out of a group of friends.
Every now and then a band emerges from a city, but it is unusual for five or ten groups to come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
