Fujimori returned to hospital for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was taken to a public hospital on Tuesday to investigate the muscle loss of his legs, his family doctor informed.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving 25 years in prison for human rights violations during his reign (1990-2000), has several diseases, including tongue cancer, which is operated and controlled four times.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a member of Congress and his personal doctor, told television that Fujimori would be examined for three days at the Peruvian Hospital Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas to determine the reason for his pain and muscle loss in the lower body members.
Aguinaga commented that he believed Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, but he did not want to do so because he thought he was innocent.
He has been operated on four times for tongue cancer and has lost 18 kilos in weight, including other diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, hypertension and circulatory problems in the legs.
Fujimori has been held at the Dirección Nacional de Operaciones Especiales de la Policia since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the Peruvian army death squad, which was secretly active during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and entrepreneurs will start their visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues of the region.
Mujica will meet with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón next Wednesday, which will be the culmination of his busy schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico, according to the Uruguayan president.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries," the South American country's presidential office announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking support from Calderón for the incident with France, when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his discourse, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that still act as tax havens, which was rejected by Uruguay and prompted a request from his ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been presiding over the G20, a group of the most powerful emerging and industrialized countries in the world, since November, and an agreement has been in place to exchange tax information to avoid double taxation with the South American country since January of this year.
In recent years, the Government of Uruguay has attempted to accelerate the concretisation of agreements for the exchange of tax information in order to be removed from the "grey list" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), which includes countries that have not implemented all international standards for cooperation in tax matters.
On a business level, a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay has been in place since 2004, which has contributed to a growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
The snoring installer enters the third dimension with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought tirelessly for 25 years to rescue Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but so far he has never been in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he fights for the girl's love in stereo technology.
The game, which comes to the shop counters all over the world this month, has been tailored from the start to the features of the Nintende 3DS portable console, which can be played three-dimensionally without a special pair of glasses.
“Mario is the figure who has to say how stereoscopy works without glasses,” said Omar Alvarez, who is in charge of the Nintendo-specialized press in Spain at the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
"Super Mario 3D Land is Nintendo's first video game to be developed for this console from the very beginning, because hit articles like Star Fox 64 3D or Zelda: Ocarine of Time 3D have been adaptations of existing titles.
Nintendo’s spokesman underlined that while it’s three-dimensional, “Super Mario 3D Land” is an “affordable” video game that allows for a fast, fluid game.
Alvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contained two games in one: The first part is "easy" to capture the less skilled users.
After that, the experts can turn a "second round" over the different levels of the game, which are becoming increasingly difficult.
In addition, users can choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action. To overcome the obstacles without being a victim of the "optical effects", however, it is always necessary to play three-dimensionally.
This trip of Super Mario into the three-dimensional world also means the character’s return to a portable console, which has not been the case since 2005.
With this video game, Nintendo winks at the fans of the saga and repeats the recipe for success of recent editions: The snoring installer must overcome dangerous platforms to free the Princess Peach.
However, the player encounters news about the movements, the environment, the disguises and the enemies - and a "playable" Luigi.
