Trinijove has helped 6,000 young people at risk of social exclusion
The organization was created to avoid marginalization of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of the life of Trinijove have led to important results: In this quarter century, 6,000 young people at risk of social exclusion were supported in order to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, there are over a hundred jobs created for this social group.
On the occasion of the anniversary, an event took place yesterday in the former factory buildings of Fabra i Coats, in which more than 300 people took part.
Trinijove was founded in 1986 in the Trinitat Vella district with the aim of helping young people with low levels of education, without work, with drug problems that were at risk of marginality.
Yesterday's celebration in Sant Andreu was attended by numerous representatives of institutions and institutions who have worked with the association for 25 years.
The participation of political representatives of different directions at election times proved the impartiality of the work done by Trinijove.
Apart from the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol participated in the celebrations of former socialist education minister Ernest Maragall and former mayor and current left-green city councilor Ricard Goma.
The large hall of Fabra i Coats was also visited by the current Catalan Minister of Social Affairs and Family Affairs, Josep Llu's Cleries, and the Director General of the Social Work of the Sparkasse La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas stressed that Trinijove was launched in very difficult times and that today’s times are no less complicated, but he added that the work done so far “is a good foundation”.
For the president of the Generalitat, Trinijove is an example that knows how to fight against difficult circumstances and gives people in difficulty hope.
“The economic crisis is nothing new for the club and the work it does,” he said.
Occupied house where giant parties were held was cleared
The homeowners had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building on Balmes No. 51 (Barcelona).
The twelve occupiers left the building last afternoon without any resistance.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbors of the house No. 51 on the street Balmes have come to an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building, which they had illegally occupied, and in which they had organized huge festivals that had driven the neighborhood to despair.
After the evacuation, the door lock was replaced to avoid a similar situation.
“From now on, access will be checked,” the house manager confirmed.
The occupiers who had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments of the building - the rest were inhabited - took the entire electrical system and part of the water supply, and they had painted the walls and left behind all kinds of garbage, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
On the three lower floors, huge parties were celebrated that lasted up to two days and drove the tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which also suffered damage from it.
Her owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that her business had declined by 80% since the start of the occupation.
The owner of the discotheque pointed out that the occupiers were unfairly competing with her, because they sold the drinks at three euros, while in the discotheque they cost 10 euros.
In addition, the owner of the leisure venue had been reported by the neighbors for rest disturbance, while according to her statement the noise did not come from the visitors of the disco, but from the house occupiers and especially from the guests of the festivals that were organized there, and which according to the angry neighbors in recent weeks became more and longer.
Discotheque officials said the harassment was so great that they agreed with the owner of the building not to pay rent for the last nine months.
The Guardia Urbana (city police) also confirmed that it has received more complaints from its neighbors in recent weeks.
The chairman of the PP (Partido Popular - People's Party) in the city council of Barcelona, Alberto Fernández Diaz, had demanded last week to clear the building immediately and to get to grips with the problems of civic coexistence and the downfall of the neighborhood.
He explained that only one floor of the building had been occupied before the summer, but that the occupiers had penetrated all the floors of the building and almost all the apartments in recent months.
In this sense, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and take action against the antisocial acts in the building."
