Park or mountain?
Apart from the disputes over the fees, the architects agree to the tender.
The municipal tender for the 16 goals reopens the debate on the importance of Collserola in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now disappeared Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this administration published its disgrace paper on the promotion of Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as a huge park in Barcelona city.
It was even compared in numbers to the Central Park of New York.
With the fall of the CMB in 1987, the park became the upper boundary of Barcelona in the eyes of many, because the capital of Catalonia is one of the few that spreads not in the north-south direction, but upwards (mountains) and downwards (sea).
The classification of Collserolas as a nature park plays with this idea.
The model was no longer the Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild boars in the role of the yogi bear.
So far, in September, the city issued a huge tender, consisting of 16 competitions, for further entrance gates to Collserola.
Without a doubt, a gate points to the concept of a park.
Either that’s the case, or someone is planning to set goals in the country.
The question arises by itself: Collserola, Park or Mountain?
The call for proposals is not only from an organisational point of view, but also with a view to a reflection on the city, the topic of discussion in the mouth of all architects from Barcelona.
It is almost a recurring theme that two members of this old caste, who meet in the elevator, can resort to.
And it is precisely this fact that provides the material for one of the rare matches between what three Barcelona architects think about it and some university professors who applied for the project.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The tender is appropriate.
For Roldán "it is necessary" to talk about the "front of the mountains" after the attack on the coast, as far as the discourse of Ildefons Cerda, who is over the green apples, has not been held.
"One should assume the principle that Barcelona's largest park is the beach.
Among other things, because it is easily accessible.
Collserola is more complex," says the architect, for whom the title "Tore of Collserola" contains a "lexical trap": one must not imagine it "as entrances to a park, but as the confines of areas where action must be taken."
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with urban planning experience, sees the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" that involves "some dangers".
Hazards arising from the "uncertainty that the design of a public space brings today" following the experiences from the 1980s, which had their "tail singing" in the field of the forum.
The first concern is to limit yourself to what can be built.
“Restricting something always means setting the next step,” i.e., exceeding it.
"You have to think about new urban planning tools, because the current [referring to the Plan General Metropolitano] can lead to a real disaster."
Modol, who is closer to the question, simplifies that the side of Collserola, which goes in the direction of Vallesana, "can be understood as a park that does not go in the direction of Barcelona", for purely topographical reasons.
Modol recalls that there is already a study by the Patronate de Collserola that should not "stood on deaf ears", although he is grateful to the city administration for giving his body the opportunity to participate in this project "from the very first moment."
In addition, he notes that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the guide letter that allows architects to participate in the debate, although he expresses his "doubt" as to whether this technical profile should lead the created multidisciplinary teams ("exactly the right one," he says) "We architects should only be a tool."
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question in the headline of this article is complex, as Collserola lacks a global view in the tendering conditions: "There have been 16 competitions in cross-section," he says, "on the mountain sea axis. But there is no longitudinal perspective that looks at the area in its entirety."
At least in his case, this led him to participate in the 16 competitions.
Otherwise, the program and definition of a project for a gate would collide with that of the architect of the gate next to it.
In his opinion, the city should absolutely guarantee that the strip is located directly above the Ronda de Dalt in its entire length in such a way that a soft transition between the city and the green zones is created.
