Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome announced details of the plane crash in which Secretary of the Government Francisco Blake and seven others were killed.
SCT (Mexico’s Secretariat of Communications and Transportation) reported that the results of the investigation into the accident, which killed Secretary of State Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people, indicate that the helicopter with its entire intact structure was directly bounced to the ground without the pilot being able to initiate an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transportation, said that the pilot had confirmed before launch that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller wing was in contact with trees at 25 meters altitude, with the helicopter losing the fuselage, seems to indicate that the helicopter had had had several ground contacts."
He also stated that the helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for transporting the personnel.
He also said that no helicopter parts were found during the investigations in the area where the machine had crashed.
"In the search, no aircraft parts were found elsewhere, the impact was on the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has an inclination of 7 to 30 degrees.
At present, it is a priority to get the results of the investigation as soon as possible, but it can take several months, perhaps even a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat of Aircraft and Auxiliary Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter from the Estado Mayor Presidencial had flown at a speed of travel and the plane had fallen on a soft slope.
"This information reinforces the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of the impact."
At a press conference, the head of SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points to be taken into account in the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with the flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of sight flight, which means that the crew should have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions at the start, and during the flight towards the border area between Mexico City and the Mexico State, some deep-hanging clouds arose.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that because of the clouds, the team had chosen a lower area with a better view towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Impact point:
The impact coordinates and the last radar record of the helicopter are consistent, and there may have been no loss of control over the aircraft or deviation from the flight route before the impact.
Dispersion of the remnants of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available up to the present time indicates that the helicopter had bounced in a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of the scattered aircraft remains suggest that the helicopter with its intact structure had impacted the ground.
No signs of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft at the site of the accident do not indicate fire or explosion.
The latest research results indicate several ground contacts.
In the field investigations, aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9,200 feet above sea level. The terrain is bulging and has a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter is likely to have broken.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had multiple ground contacts.
After a minute search in an area that went beyond the locked area at the site of the accident, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, which reinforces the assumption that the intact aircraft structure had bounced against the ground.
MSS Announces Research Protocol to Find the Gene for Obesity
She heads a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, which is supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Mexico's Social Insurance Institute) announced that it is leading a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of childhood and youth obesity" to find the genetic markers associated with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquimica (Department of Medical Research, focus on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, explained that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutrition specialists and social workers was set up.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate course at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Peblica (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested parties can come to the sports fields of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where tests with children and adolescents are conducted every Saturday from 8.00 am.
He stressed that the investigation began on the sports field of Cuauhtémoc (in the west of the state of México) and has continued since 8 October on the sports field of Nezahualcóyolt (in the east of the state of México).
Once the target of 500 to 600 investigators has been reached, the study will be continued on the sports field of Independencia (in the south of the capital district) and will be completed on that of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to get to know the factors and the role of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors of Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the global day of diabetes, he stated that it is intended that three thousand children and adolescents aged six to 14 should fill out nutritional questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They are also asked questions about their physical activity and family history of disease to control risk factors that could result in diabetes or kidney failure.
He also stated that on those Saturdays the subjects were measured (weight, size, waist circumference), their blood pressure controlled and blood levels such as glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (trying to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López stressed that this investigation would be carried out on the occasion of health workers’ concerns about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years, the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent, and obesity also increased dramatically," said the IMSS specialist.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico differed from that of other peoples.
He stated that on average, a Mexican is 65 percent Native American, 30 percent European and 5 percent African, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he explained that the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn the excess of the energy we consume (calories) so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the study participants would be a comprehensive examination of the children, which would determine whether they had a degree of obesity or obesity.
It would even investigate the occurrence of dark skin wrinkles in the neck and inner arm (acanthesis), indicating the likelihood of metabolic disorders and pre-stage diabetes.
All information would be treated confidentially and communicated to the parents in writing by the doctors. The doctors explain to the parents all the measurement results and propose to them lifestyle changes that are appropriate for the prevention of diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three fundamental factors responsible for obesity, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, i.e. lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transport, instead of short distances walking.
The high calorie intake, i.e. an increased consumption of sugared beverages and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) along with a high fat and protein intake, as well as the genetics to be analyzed in this research project.
UNAM asphalt prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, Researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM, develops polymer-modified asphalts to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs emanating from the road surface were observed, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 potholes if the rainy season in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (Valley of Mexico) erupted, Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, said, cautioning and even insuring that the pothole count would be significantly reduced.
In his lecture, "Trackholes from a technical point of view", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for is developing polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but which has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of the road surface, thus avoiding the appearance of potholes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes.
Toughening-elastic behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180° C., at 120° C. it is very viscous and almost solid at 50° C., while it becomes fragile at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer said.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City mostly have flexible road surfaces, which consist of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers is a layer of asphalt, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single piece of this layer of wear was bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move on and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
“If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better,” said the chemical engineer.
"Above the wear layer," he explained, "a final layer is laid out, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tires, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it must produce friction.
Those of this road surface that receives and distributes the most forces, the support layer also needs a suitable thickness and the material it is made of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially the water, because it significantly impairs the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes moist, water enters the layer and exits only with difficulty. This causes softening of all layers of the road surface and, as a result, the appearance of potholes.
When a impact hole is formed, "the cover layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only affected afterwards, but the damage is not immediately caused, but it is a process that would have to be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (Mexico’s National Research System) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause of the occurrence of impact holes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be proportional to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent impact holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes could be repaired easily and without the use of high temperatures.
