This was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano.
A lophoscopicist from Cali went into history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
Last November 4, a lophoscopicist of the Cali State Prosecutor’s Investigation Unit (CTI) as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia - Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia) entered: “Alfonso Cano” by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopicists in the CTI department, this week Eliazar González had on-call service, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in communities of Chocó, where he often had to go to the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to Valle over and after completing the necessary courses he specialized in Lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin that is exposed to friction, i.e. the palms and feet.
In the week of the campaign against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big awaited him.
Friday night he flew in a helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he should identify two bodies, and that there was a suspicion that one could be that of the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he should take along Guillermo León Sáenz’s 10-finger print sheet (his real name).
However, when he reached the location where the body was, he could not identify it because of its physical appearance, for this was not in the least similar to the images he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a farmer in the area, was not wearing glasses and was much thinner.
Fingerprints do not lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a planter and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse to those on the imprint sheet.
He said it was Alfonso Cano.
That same night, this Puerto Tejada man was in charge of informing the Defense Minister, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was indeed the head of the FARC.
On track search
For a dactyloscope from Sijin in Cali, the appreciation given by President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference on the campaign against "Cano" was very important.
Many people don’t know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science with no error rate, which can be a key factor in the resolution of a crime.
Lophoscopicists not only identify bodies, they also support investigations into murder and robbery and confirm the identity of the arrested persons.
When they are arrested, many offenders present false identity documents or they do not have one.
We take the fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The researcher told us that he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house in the event of a theft, because the thief had supported himself with his hand right here when he pulled out a safe stuffed with jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are inappropriate for taking fingerprints, but in this case we were able to take the imprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in several thefts," he recalled.
With the help of fingerprints, murder suspects can also be relieved or burdened.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by liquor bottles.
In the investigation, it was suspected that a family member might be suspicious, and in fact a fingerprint on the bottle agreed.
Although this does not guarantee that the killer is involved, he is still associated with the place where the crime was committed.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that “the fingerprints with chemical or physical reagents would be taken from the object.”
When they appear, a planting cell or band is used to take them with you.
After that, the prints are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the civil registry office.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identification papers," the CTI expert explained.
He said not everything was the way it was portrayed in the TV series SCI.
Just as not all gold is what shines, not all you touch is a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you make a comparison.
The “Disgruntled” Challenge New York Authorities
Hundreds of demonstrators gathered in tents on Zuccotti Square.
Much of it followed the eviction order and changed its location to a nearby park.
On Tuesday, members of the Ocupy Wall Street movement challenged New York authorities as they tried again with a court order to enter Manhattan Square after being cleared of the square at dawn and trying to occupy another place at the Big Apple.
Hundreds of demonstrators gathered in front of Zuccotti Square, to which they sought access with a court order allowing the "embarrassed" to camp again at this site. Meanwhile, another part of the movement clung to the eviction order and occupied a park further north in the city, where nine arrests occurred.
“Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to camp on the pitch, we will meet in another place and continue the battle with legal means to return to Zuccotti, with sit-ins and peaceful demonstrations,” said Mark Bray, a spokesman for the Ocupy Wall Street movement.
Bray stated that the “outrages”’ response to the eviction of her tent camp, which had been ordered directly by Michael Bloomberg, the mayor of New York, came to court, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting the violent eviction of the square and authorizing the demonstrators to camp.
In addition, the "embarrassed" occupied a new park located at the intersection of centrally located Canal Street and Sixth Avenue very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel connecting New York and New Jersey, which is owned by Trinity Church.
They were able to occupy the place for at least an hour, but then the police arrived and arrested some of the protesters, although Bray cannot give exact numbers. He assured the news agency Efe that he had seen several journalists with handcuffs among them.
The organization assures that hundreds of people have arrived at this place, where also a delegation of religious leaders had arrived as a sign of their support of the members of the movement and for mediation with the police.
