Some of the square-driven protesters carried and distributed photocopies of this court order, even giving them to some police officers who guarded the square, resulting in "a few small clashes," Bray reported, who reported that some police officers had beaten protesters.
The court order forbids the authorities to remove members of Occupy Wall Street from the court, as well as the application of “laws passed after the occupation and prohibiting the demonstrators from returning to the park with their tents and other items they had previously used.”
Mayor Bloomberg made it clear to the press that this court order had lifted the reopening of the square for the public and the demonstrators, pointing out to the protesters that the city laws did not allow them to re-establish themselves with tents and sleeping bags at the site.
The mayor personally defended the eviction of Zuccotti Square at dawn, where nearly 200 people were arrested, and which was decided because the protesters "violate the law."
Bloomberg said he gave the order to clear the square because it had “turned into a place where people didn’t come to demonstrate, but to break the laws, and in some cases to harm other people,” because “some deals had received threats” and residents were “fearful of their quality of life.”
“The eviction at dawn was disgusting and shows that Bloomberg is basically interested in protecting financial interests and not protecting the interests of North American workers,” the movement’s spokesman added, accusing the mayor of “not respecting the freedom of the press.”
Occupy Wall Street officials said they thought about organizing “great actions” for Thursday, along with community organizations and trade unions, to commemorate the two months that the protests have been going on since September 17.
