Japan is reborn after the earthquake
GDP grows by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the free fall spiral from the beginning of March
Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still recovering from the destructive earthquake that led to a nuclear crisis and the worst catastrophe Japan had experienced during World War II.
The government’s initial estimates in Tokyo estimated the damage to property at $300,000, a blow that seems to be attenuating despite the difficult global economic situation.
After three quarters, gross domestic product data from July to September finally closed this chapter: GDP grew by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% to the year-on-year ratio.
The value measured in the second quarter - in Japan, the fiscal year starts in March 2012 - also means the fastest growth since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery can be explained in part by the sale of machinery for the reconstruction of the areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1% compared to the 0.9% decrease for investments recorded from January to March, the first decline after six months of unstoppable increases.
Nevertheless, the real shift in the Japanese economy is not based solely on Keynesian impulses that use the crisis to build or rebuild infrastructure.
Japan has woken up thanks in particular to the development of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by growing spending on vehicles, travel and leisure.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo has entrusted itself to the domestic market after the yen - the Japanese currency - has moved into one of the "refugee currencies" of investors fleeing from the eurozone's debt crisis and bleak forecasts for the U.S., a privilege that bears a tombstone on the accounts of export companies.
With a harder currency, the products abroad are more expensive, a serious problem for a country whose economy is based on the health of major technology producers.
Toyota and Sony, for example, attributed their weak business results from July to September to the listing of the yen.
While markets continue to besiege peripheral EU countries, the Yoshihiko Noda government remains vigilant.
“We need to pay attention to the ongoing risks, for example the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid upgrading of the yen,” said the State Secretary for Economic Policy, Motohisa Furukawa.
The perspectives are really not very uplifting.
The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) said that most member states showed clearer signs of a slowdown in economic development in September.
The indicator predicting the turning points of the global economy showed that the brakes on the biggest economic potentials had been pulled.
Because he dropped by four tenths to 100.4 points compared to the 100.8 in August.
The eurozone is even below this average, which is 100 after falling by eight tenths to 99.13 points.
