Euthanasia and accompanied free death must be legalized, according to an expert panel
Canadians live in denial of death, according to a report by the Royal Society of Canada
The panel stated that governments, healthcare institutions and doctors worked together to provide the best pain relievers, including beyond cancer cases.
The Canadian society lives in a denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians actually agree to talk to their doctor about conditions in which they want to die and make dispositions for this purpose.
This is one of the conclusions of an imposing Royal Society of Canada report involving six experts linked to each other in various fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
This body recommends that the government amend the criminal law in such a way as to allow accompanied suicide and euthanasia where this choice arises, specifically for patients who are considered to be able to make such a decision.
As a prelude, the experts cite a recently published survey by the independent company EIU, which had compared the quality of death in 40 countries of the world.
Although Canada has ranked 10th in this, the study notes that "medical death care in Canada has produced a culture in which people are afraid to cut the topic of death."
Medical care or not: 77% of Canadians do not have access to painkillers, according to experts appointed by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the majority of Canadians wanting to die at home, 68.6% of those eventually die in hospital.
From a country-wide perspective, the rate is highest in Quebec, with 86% of hospital deaths.
In the delicate question of euthanasia and accompanying suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that are opposed to the position of the federal government, which has already expressed no desire to make any changes to the criminal law on euthanasia and accompanying suicide.
However, according to the experts who have inspected all those countries whose approach has legalized or decriminalized euthanasia and accompanied suicide, there is no evidence that such decriminalisation would entail misuse in its application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or accompanied suicide by incompetent or non-conforming persons.
On the contrary, much more cases of such violations are encountered, especially in countries where euthanasia and accompanying suicide are not legalized, as Jocelyn Downie, co-signator of the report, confirmed in a teleconference yesterday.
“Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal.”
“Accompanied suicide is also practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal here,” explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians support euthanasia
Recall that, according to an Angus-Reid survey conducted in 2010, 85% of Canadians had already emigrated in favor of euthanasia, as they believe it will allow people at the end of their lives to alleviate their suffering.
And 66% believe that the fact of legalizing euthanasia does not result in conveying the message that the lives of elderly or disabled people are of less value.
