Energy policy:
Facts should win over dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or on the basis of emotions, this is certainly energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to take an election meeting as an opportunity to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is driving a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, and a huge proportion of the world’s population should not have to give up a vital element.
At the same time, it is necessary to mitigate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to fight against climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which subjects its decision to the need to find a substitute source, nor in Switzerland, which just intends to build only last-generation nuclear power plants.
Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
The United States, after Fukushima, has decided to join another unit in its park by restarting the Three Mile Island plant, which was shut down after the nuclear accident.
Although the German model focused on renewable energy sources is occasionally set as a model, reality contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will result in an increase in the price of electricity, an increased dependence on energy, especially from Russia, due to the increased use of imported gas, and an increase in CO2 emissions from gas and coal-fired power plants.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will be noticeable within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives cause for reflection.
Denmark, on the one hand, is the European leader in wind energy, from which it draws 30% of its electricity, on the other hand, is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, used alternately with wind energy; as a result, its CO2 emissions and electricity prices are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than our French households.
Since the energy price in the globalised economy is a key part of competitiveness and a stable asset for industry on national soil, French companies have an advantage because of the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore result in a sharp increase in energy prices, which would make the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys found that it was a price that the vast majority of French people are just as unwilling to pay as it shows resistance to the principle of this energy source.
Let us remember that our country’s energy policy has made it possible to build an industry with 125.00 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a large number of specialized small and medium-sized companies to the international markets and makes them the creators of countless jobs.
If France decides to quit nuclear power, most of these SMEs would be affected and the annual €6 billion of capital goods and nuclear energy exports would shrink more and more.
Which electrician would hire an EPR designed to work for sixty years, if the decline of its producer is pre-programmed?
In order to solve the energetic equation, one must admit that there is no miracle like a devil’s work for the production of electricity.
The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy testify to the complementarity of the energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a security agency that carries out uncompromising and transparent checks in existing plants, such as the Flamanville construction site.
Their work teams, who have made a name for themselves because of their professionalism, are just obsessed with the idea of security.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only one, in Three Mile Island, has entered under normal operating conditions; so it went without consequences for humans and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was evoked by reactor construction and inexcusable human failure.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident caused by two unprecedented natural disasters caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will draw its lessons from this accident, just as it had done after the two preceding ones.
As a result of this approach and a cooperation of the safety authorities of the French and German operators and designers of nuclear power plants, the EPR presents a draft which enables it to be resilient to such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among electrical engineers to build a nuclear power plant, a construction stop in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition from Areva and EDF by letting them take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is indispensable and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party manoeuvres dominate a debate that also determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
