The immigration policy led by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from many angles - overloading of police, judicial and administrative bodies due to a policy subject to the figures, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "land of human rights", as France had called itself.
Recently, the harassment of foreign students by the authorities had shaped the press reports, the Interior Minister had casually announced (see Libération of 23 May) that France "does not need any talents, masons or waiters from abroad".
But this policy has rarely been analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
On the right was the tone of Jacques Chirac, who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including over 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country", on the left by Michel Rocard, who had stated in 1990 that France "could not take up all the poverty in the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
The fear of the invasion of national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared by both the right and the left in 2005.
The immigrants were perceived by both camps as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity one is willing to admit to immigrants.
In his programme, Francois Hollande confines himself to banalities that indicate that partnership development allows us to solve our "migration problems".
This idea of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on elections; however, it is economically costly.
As economic experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron remind us of in a recent work that summarizes the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of immigrants’ jobs and on the growth of their economies.
Restricting immigration would dampen growth and harm the labour market situation.
Fears of migrant influence are based on the notion that they threaten to replace the local workforce, especially the less skilled, by exerting pressure on their wages.
However, experience shows that immigrants are in fact much more complementary than domestic wage workers, as they focus on professions in sectors that are untapped in terms of workplace technology.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that attract local wage workers little, the more qualified among immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not aligned with the job offer.
Positive pay effect
Just as a surgeon would find it difficult to work in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthetists, this complementarity also has a positive effect on wages and domestic labour market conditions between locals and migrants.
Giovanni Peri has calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants will result in a co-involved, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas brought in by immigrants is beneficial, as well as economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
The migrants also contribute net to the social systems, in the European countries on average at about 1% of the total budget.
For example, the World Labour Organization estimates that an immigrant to Germany at the age of 30 will contribute on average a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to bring about the missing intersections "with the teeth" at the start of his mandate.
However, these said teeth, which were supposed to deter immigrants, achieved exactly the opposite effect.
