Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is expected to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with splendour and Gloria.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new gas pipeline Nord Stream, which connects Russia and Germany directly under sea level, on the Baltic Sea coast last Tuesday under orchestral sounding and at gourmet buffet.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Francois Fillon and his colleague Mark Rutte from the Netherlands have symbolically jointly turned the control of the valve, which transports the Russian gas to the Western European network.
The new gas pipeline is expected to deliver 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas per year to Western Europe through a first pipeline of 1,224 km that connects the Saint Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic meters of gas – the equivalent of France’s total consumption – is expected to be completed by the end of 2012.
And you already let the eventuality of the construction of a third line sound on the same track.
For Gazprom, the timely and punctual completion of this enormous structure seems like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream pipeline will allow for direct gas delivery to Germany, while avoiding any trajectory by third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing a bit of their power: it is now becoming more difficult for them to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close off access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most engaged in the debate, did not shy away from comparing the Nord Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet pact" in connection with the Hitler-Stalin alliance for the purpose of the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply through the support of this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of a demolition of European energy, as the project has struck a break between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In barely five years, Russia has succeeded in enforcing its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which have strong gas consumption and their gas reserves are depleted.
“This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way,” Fillon said at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out to what extent the large gas contracts are important from the political and economic side.
All this explains the broad smile of the Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding the gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with concrete casing, which is to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at about 200 m depth.
During their construction, minefields dating from World War II had to be avoided.
“Approximately hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect fauna and flora.
The line is a long queue made of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which is interrupted over the entire length by nothing: neither by valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers have refrained from it, as the Swedes were not keen to see a Russian state company settle at the level of their coasts in a permanent manner.
"In the event of an accident, we close the gas passage in less than a minute," Jens Müller said.
In the event of a leak, the gas located in the gas pipeline thus escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered by the designers to be less likely, as the seams were estimated to have a perpetuity of one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot, which is controlled for external observation purposes by a sea ship, and by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, with a diameter of one meter, is inserted into the interior of the pipeline and moved through the gas pressure.
After three full days of moving through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on its arrival about any deformations of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo even the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entry point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated (each 15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gas Union and the French group of companies GDF Suez (each 9%).
These five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company, on a 20-year contract that could be extended.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the amount of gas that is actually transported," Jens Müller said.
The financing of gas pipeline construction was secured by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should amount to 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amount was 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are willing to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the liability risk.
The gas pipeline is found on a sandy, pine-forested coastal stretch near Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other parameters of the incoming gas before it is passed on to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per passing hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Founded by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give new style to writing.
It has a flair of adventure, hours spent at candlelight with writing.
Moleskine's notebook is easily recognizable again, with its black, rectangular cover, its rubber band, the egg-shell-colored sides, as aged over time.
