The Italian company Modo Modo, which is based in Milan, decided to launch a distinctive design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then specialist consultant of the company, is tasked with the market launch of the new product.
The notebook was inspired by an ancient production technique called Mole Skin, which designates a cotton back used, for example, for upholstered benches.
This type of notebook was very popular among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten object, which was considered an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success comes in.
Sales increased by 26% between 2006 and 2010, with sales of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were conceived.
Moleskine passes the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create a phantom image of the buyers, as the notebook delights businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultured and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which initially had 12 employees, now employs more than 100 people and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
The company distributes its notebooks in bookstores, on internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques in the city centers and is committed to enforcing its identity.
“We have followed the spirit of the times and its new writing needs, which persists despite the upswing of the emails,” said Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the company Moleskine: Recently, the brand launched an exhibition called "Detour (detour)", in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a leopard pattern cover for the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine benefited from his success and this cultural spirit of the times and understood how to diversify his products: bags, schedules, fillers, computer cases... The brand has the full range of articles.
In the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the Investment Fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, and thus opened a new chapter in the history of Moleskine.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
Approximately 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
Today begins the 15th Week of Work for the Disabled.
Despite a deliberate publicity policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people is always twice as high as the average: 19% against 9% of the total population.
Discouraging?
"No," said Eric Blanchet, Director-General of the Adapt Association, which organizes the "week of work for the disabled."
"The progress made within fifteen years is considerable."
At the time, the unemployment rate was not double, but triple as high.
"However, there is still a lot to do."
However, it must be said that many obstacles remain for the disabled before they get a job.
It affects older people more often: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them do not have a high school diploma and there are only 10,000 disabled students among the 2.3 million students with higher education.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% for the disabled compared to 38% on average.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to get back to work and that "form the core of the problem," says Christian Grapin, Director-General of Tremplin, a association founded in 1992 that helps companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the real brakes.
Remains the unspoken, the mental attitudes, which are certainly developing, but are slowly evolving.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprentre association for the journal La Cité stated that the managers surveyed have “a weak level of knowledge about disabled people” that “overrepresented” is “of persons in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually disabled.”
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the employment target of 6% disabled workers, which was stipulated in a 1987 law.
These latter figures from 2008 point to a quotient of 2.6%.
“We are now around 3%,” reports Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the organization tasked with collecting contributions from companies that violate this law.
Proof: The number of "paying" establishments, as well as the sum of the amounts paid, has decreased from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros) between 2007 and 2011.
“The 2005 law, which provides for contribution increases, created a strong pressure on companies,” Pierre Blanc said.
"But this improvement also shows a real insight, especially among the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of workplaces between 20 and 49 employees employ disabled workers, while companies with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
